      "writtenOn": "2018-11-27T23:35:30Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "What happens if you receive a data packet that\u0027s 4 bytes?\n\nYou should instead have some member variable that you use to track what you expect to receive. For example, you could set nextSize to MAX_INT when you expect to get a new size and then your code would be something like:\n\nif (hwCarCluster-\u003enextSize \u003d\u003d MAX_INT) {\n  if (msglen !\u003d 4) {\n    // some sort of error\n  }\n  hwCarCluster-\u003enextSize \u003d (reinterpret_cast\u003cint32_t *\u003e msg)[0];\n} else {\n  hwCarCluster-\u003ecallback(reinterpret_cast\u003cchar *\u003emsg, hwCarCluster-\u003enextSize);\n  hwCarCluster-\u003enextSize \u003d MAX_INT;\n}\n\nAlternatively just have an explicit boolean for \"expectingData\" or something.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 57,
        "startChar": 8,
        "endLine": 57,
        "endChar": 19
      },
      "revId": "2345f6a174b09fd0466dcab418aa8b65d051e19c",
